{"title_page": "Lake Louisa State Park", "text_new": "{{redirect|Lake Louisa|the lake in Minnesota|Murray County, Minnesota}}\n{{distinguish|Lake Louise State Park}}\n{{short description|Park in Florida, USA}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Lake Louisa State Park\n| iucn_category = III\n| map = Florida\n| map_caption = \n| location = [[Lake County, Florida]], [[United States|USA]]\n| nearest_city = [[Clermont, Florida]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|28|28|01|N|81|45|29|W|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| area = {{convert|4372|acre|km2}}\n| established = \n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = [[Florida Department of Environmental Protection]]\n}}\n\n'''Lake Louisa State Park''' is a {{convert|4372|acre|km2|adj=on}} [[Florida State Parks|Florida State Park]] located south of [[Clermont, Florida|Clermont]], in the northeast corner of the [[Green Swamp (Florida)|Green Swamp]] and the southwestern shore of Lake Louisa.  It is made up of [[bald cypress]], [[live oak]], and [[saw palmetto]]s. In addition to Lake Louisa, the park contains Hammond Lake, Dixie Lake, Dude Lake, Bear Lake, and several smaller lakes.\n\nTwo small streams, Big Creek and Little Creek, flow north from the Green Swamp through the park into Lake Louisa.  Lake Louisa is the source of the [[Palatlakaha River]], one of the headwaters of the [[Ocklawaha River]].\n\nThe main entrance to the park is on [[U.S. Route 27#Florida|U.S. 27]] {{convert|7|mi|km}} south of [[Florida State Road 50|State Road 50]].  Another entrance on the western side of the park, off [[County Road 561 (Lake County, Florida)|County Route 561]] on Lake Nellie Road, gives access only to a beach on Lake Louisa and to the horse trails.\n\nActivities include swimming, picnicking, horseback riding, hiking, camping, fishing, and canoeing. Amenities include a canoe/kayak ramp, {{convert|16|mi|km}} of equestrian trails, and a primitive equestrian campground, as well as a {{convert|0.5|mi|km|adj=on}} nature trail, {{convert|20|mi|km}} of hiking trails, fishing pier, canoe/kayak launch, and a picnic pavilion. The park is open from 8:00 am till sundown year-round.\n\nThe property was purchased by the state in 1973 and opened to the public in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.floridastateparks.org/history/parkhistory.cfm?parkid=105|publisher=Florida Division of Recreation and Parks|title=Lake Louisa State Park: History and Culture|accessdate=2014-11-30}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Lake Louisa State Park.jpg|[[Bald Cypress]] in Lake Louisa\nFile:Osprey nests.jpg|[[Osprey]]s are common in the park's lakes\nFile:FL Lake Louisa SP west01.jpg|\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n* [https://www.floridastateparks.org/parks-and-trails/lake-louisa-state-park Lake Louisa State Park] at [https://www.floridastateparks.org Florida State Parks]\n* [http://www.abfla.com/parks/LakeLouisa/lakelouisa.html Lake Louisa State Park] at [http://www.abfla.com Absolutely Florida]\n* [http://areas.wildernet.com/pages/area.cfm?areaID=FLSPLL&CU_ID=1 Lake Louisa State Park] at [http://www.wildernet.com Wildernet]\n\n{{Protected areas of Florida}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Parks in Lake County, Florida]]\n[[Category:State parks of Florida]]\n\n\n{{Florida-state-park-stub}}\n{{LakeCountyFL-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Lake Louisa|the lake in Minnesota|Murray County, Minnesota}}\n{{distinguish|Lake Louise State Park}}\n{{short description|Park in Florida, USA}}\n{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Lake Louisa State Park\n| iucn_category = III\n| map = Florida\n| map_caption = \n| location = [[Lake County, Florida]], [[United States|USA]]\n| nearest_city = [[Clermont, Florida]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|28|28|01|N|81|45|29|W|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| area = {{convert|4372|acre|km2}}\n| established = \n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = [[Florida Department of Environmental Protection]]\n}}\n\n'''Lake Louisa State Park''' is a {{convert|4372|acre|km2|adj=on}} [[Florida State Parks|Florida State Park]] located south of [[Clermont, Florida|Clermont]], in the northeast corner of the [[Green Swamp (Florida)|Green Swamp]] and the southwestern shore of Lake Louisa.  It is made up of [[bald cypress]], [[live oak]] and [[saw palmetto]]s. In addition to Lake Louisa, the park contains Hammond Lake, Dixie Lake, Dude Lake, Bear Lake and several smaller lakes.\n\nTwo small streams, Big Creek and Little Creek, flow north from the Green Swamp through the park into Lake Louisa.  Lake Louisa is the source of the [[Palatlakaha River]], one of the headwaters of the [[Ocklawaha River]].\n\nThe main entrance to the park is on [[U.S. Route 27#Florida|U.S. 27]] {{convert|7|mi|km}} south of [[Florida State Road 50|State Road 50]].  Another entrance on the western side of the park, off [[County Road 561 (Lake County, Florida)|County Route 561]] on Lake Nellie Road, gives access only to a beach on Lake Louisa and to the horse trails.\n\nActivities include swimming, picnicking, horseback riding, hiking, camping, fishing, and canoeing. Amenities include a canoe/kayak ramp, {{convert|16|mi|km}} of equestrian trails, and a primitive equestrian campground, as well as a {{convert|0.5|mi|km|adj=on}} nature trail, {{convert|20|mi|km}} of hiking trails, fishing pier, canoe/kayak launch, and a picnic pavilion. The park is open from 8:00 am till sundown year-round.\n\nThe property was purchased by the state in 1973 and opened to the public in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.floridastateparks.org/history/parkhistory.cfm?parkid=105|publisher=Florida Division of Recreation and Parks|title=Lake Louisa State Park: History and Culture|accessdate=2014-11-30}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Lake Louisa State Park.jpg|[[Bald Cypress]] in Lake Louisa\nFile:Osprey nests.jpg|[[Osprey]]s are common in the park's lakes\nFile:FL Lake Louisa SP west01.jpg|\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline}}\n* [https://www.floridastateparks.org/parks-and-trails/lake-louisa-state-park Lake Louisa State Park] at [https://www.floridastateparks.org Florida State Parks]\n* [http://www.abfla.com/parks/LakeLouisa/lakelouisa.html Lake Louisa State Park] at [http://www.abfla.com Absolutely Florida]\n* [http://areas.wildernet.com/pages/area.cfm?areaID=FLSPLL&CU_ID=1 Lake Louisa State Park] at [http://www.wildernet.com Wildernet]\n\n{{Protected areas of Florida}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Parks in Lake County, Florida]]\n[[Category:State parks of Florida]]\n\n\n{{Florida-state-park-stub}}\n{{LakeCountyFL-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "179.53.163.135", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Louisa_State_Park"}
{"title_page": "Seetha (serial)", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian television series}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Seetha\n\u0d38\u0d40\u0d24\n| show_name_2              = \u0d38\u0d40\u0d24\n| image                    = Seetha_Serial_(Flowers_TV,_2017-present).jpg\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Drama]]<br />[[Romance film|Romance]]\n| producer                 = Binu.K.Ponnoose\n| writer                   = Dhanus\n| director                 = Girish Konni\n| company                  = BEE GEE Communications\n| starring                 = \n| opentheme                = Nizhalinte Nerukil Aardramai\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 674 \n| network                  = [[Flowers (TV channel)]]\n| country                  = [[India]]\n| location                 = \n| language                 = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]\n| editor                   = \n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 20 Min approx.\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = Keen FX\n| first_aired              = {{start date|df=yes|2017|2|20}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flowerstv.in/video/seetha-flowers-ep-01.cms|title=Seetha episode 1}}</ref>\n| last_aired               = \n{{end date|df=yes|2019|8|16}} \n| preceded_by              = Moonumani\n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = [[Chinthavishtayaya Seetha]]\n| website                  = https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLMzoNdm5sTvXc-VyR86IXzBawr028Ww-v\n| website_title            = Youtube link\n}}\n\n'''''Seetha''''' (Malayalam: \u0d38\u0d40\u0d24) is an [[Indian cinema|Indian]] [[television series]] in Malayalam language.\n\nThe series premiered from 20 February 2017 launched on [[Flowers (TV channel)|Flowers TV]] from Monday to Friday 7:00 PM., later changed to 6:30 PM  titled as ''Seetha'' as a second part and with the same cast of the serial [[Chinthavishtayaya Seetha]] aired on [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]]. In the first time of Malayalam television industry, a live shoot of an episode was telecast on 5 August 2018 which showed ''Seetha-Indran'' marriage from 6:00 pm to 8:00 pm. It is one of the top rated serial on Malayalam Television and the lead pair [[Swasika ]] and [[Shanavas]] earned a huge fan base due to their on-screen chemistry. The series also has a huge following on social media and Youtube Channel.\n\nThe show went off air on 16 August 2019. But due to the show's popularity, the team plans a third season.\n{{div col|colwidth=}}\n\n== Plot ==\n\nSeetha is the only earning member of her family. She runs a family of her aged parents, her sister and her brother. Indran ([[Shanavas Shanu]]) being her moracherukkan (her father's sister's son) dreams of marrying her and is obsessed about his love for her. Sreeraman ([[Bipin Jose]]) and Seetha being college mates fall in love and decide to marry with the permission of their parents. Indran befriends [[Loan Shark]] Prathapan and later discovers that he also have enmity with Seetha as she refused to illegally allow him to do his business due to village panchayat rules. After lots of difficulties and hurdles, they finally marry. Much to their dismay, with the constant interference from Indran ([[Shanavas Shanu]]) and Shankaran Maman (Sreeraman's uncle), misunderstandings and fights crop in between them. Indran along with Prathapan plots to constantly destroy Seethas married life. In Parallel track, Indran who realises he can't get Seetha decides to marry Janaki ([[Ambili Devi]]) as a bid to show Seetha that he can have a happier married life. Unknowingly, he develops feelings for Janaki, to which she also reciprocates. Meanwhile a [[Loan Shark]] Prathapan now finds his plan of revenge to Seetha failing, plans to plot against Seetha and Indran by cunningly setting them up in a hotel room unknown to them and calls the press and gets them arrested. This incident sends shock waves to both Raman and Janaki. Raman and Seetha's relationship starts to further deteriorate. Seetha attempts suicide to which Indran comes as a savoir and takes her to hospital. Raman who rushes nick in time professes that he loves Seetha deeply, thus saving her from giving in to death. Seeing this, Indran develops a respectful attitude towards Seetha and gives up his revenge plan. Janaki, who fails to believe Indran, breaks her engagement. In a fit of rejection, Indran resorts alcoholism. Seetha, who feels equally responsible for ruining Indran's life, stops him from drinking by offering a position of being her angel guardian. As Sreeraman discovers that he is diagnosed with a brain tumor that's incurable, he decides to divorce Seetha out of love. He hides this ill fate from Seetha and divorces her. He then takes his childhood friend Janaki to accompany him for his treatment through natural medicine in an asram.\n\nMeanwhile, Indran, a changed man now, enters Seetha's life by asking her to marry him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/seetha-to-marry-indran/articleshow/64177184.cms|title=Seetha to marry Indran}}</ref> She, after being persuaded by her family and Vinayan sir decides to give love and marriage a second chance. Enter, Raman, who still claim to love Seetha but is shattered to know that Seetha has indeed moved on and will never be his.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/seetha-lashes-out-at-raman/articleshow/64510555.cms|title=Seetha leaves Raman}}</ref> Raman attempts suicide and is saved by his home nurse in the nick of time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/raman-contemplating-suicide/articleshow/64635283.cms|title=Raman attempts to take his life}}</ref> Seetha makes it clear to Raman that she would never marry him, making him think of his life in future. Seetha and Indran get married in a big grandeur.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/seetha-indran-wedding-to-go-live/articleshow/65258762.cms|title=Seetha-Indran marriage live on air}}</ref>. Enter Adi Lakshmi who claims to be the illegitimate daughter of Sreedharan. Indran and Seetha's marriage faces turbulances due to Indran keeping Adi Lakshmi's truth away. Meanwhile, Sreedharan decides to donate his kidney to the ailing Adi Lakshmi's mother as he is guilty of not been responsible all this while. \nSreeraman finds love for the second time and marries Devika with the presence of all his relatives and loved ones. During the wedding, Sreeraman's uncle, Prathapan and S.I. Sugunan conspires to kill Devika as a revenge, but Devika's father gets killed in process as he consumes the unknown poisonous juice that was meant for Devika. Devika and Devika's mother decide to live in Sreeram's home after their marriage.\n\n==Cast==\n\n;Lead cast\n* [[Swasika|Swasika Vijay]] as ''Seetha Indran''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/the-prime-time-beauties-of-malayalam-tv/articleshow/63972745.cms|title= Swasika as Seetha}}</ref>\n* [[Shanavas shanu]] as ''Indran''\n\n;Supporting cast\n* Sruthy Surendran (Manve) as ''Archana Giridhar''\n* [[Ambika Mohan]]/Roslin as ''Nalini''\n* T.S.Raju as ''Sreedharan''\n* Naveen Arakkal as ''Raghuvaran''\n* [[Ronson Vincent]] as ''Jatayu Dharman''\n* Shalu Kurian as ''Aadhilekshmi''\n* Bipin Jose as ''Sreeraman''<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/the-dapper-dudes/articleshow/64002122.cms|title= Bipin Jose as Sreeraman}}</ref>\n* Baby Riya as ''Charumol''\n*Gauri Krishna as ''Devika''\n* [[Ambili Devi]]  as ''Janaki''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/dance-is-what-i-am-the-most-passionate-about-ambili-devi/articleshow/61711677.cms|title= Ambili Devi as Janaki}}</ref>\n* Jaseela Parveen as ''Shreya Chacko Thattinpurath''\n* Varsha as ''Annamma''\n* Apsara as ''ACP Mariya / Mariyakutty''\n* Subhash Menon as \"Prathapan\"\n* Sabarinath as ''Sasimohan''\n* Sindhu Jacob as ''Aadhilekshmi's mother'' \n* Omana Ouseph as ''Saradamma''\n* Kishore as \"S.I Sugunan\"\n* Anzil Rahman as \"Mohan\"\n* Adhithyan Jayan as \"Anirudhan\"\n* Jijo Varghese Antony as \"C.I Madhavan\"\n;Earlier Cast\n* Harishanth as ''Vaishakhan/Minister''\n* Saranya Sasi as ''Vaidehi''\n* Kottayam Rashid as ''Karunan''\n*Amith as ''Mathukutty ''\n* Deepan Murali<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/seetha-actor-deepan-murali-gets-engaged/articleshow/62230031.cms|title= Deepan Murali aka Giri gets married}}</ref> as ''Giridhar''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/the-dapper-dudes/articleshow/64002122.cms|title= Deepan Murali as Giridhar}}</ref>\n* Manju Satheesh as ''Jaya Sree''\n* Faisal Razi as ''Ganesh''\n* [[Sajitha Betti]] as ''Adv.Fathima Beevi''\n* Baby Vaiga as ''Ganga Giridhar''\n* Ann maria as ''Meera''\n* [[Balachandran Chullikkadu]] as ''Guruji''\n* Prakrithi as ''Sreedevi''\n* Pratheeksha G. Pradeep as ''Mythili''\n* Saritha.B.Nair as ''Mrs.Vinayan''\n* [[Leona Lishoy|Lishoy]] as Meera's father\n* Sreedevi Anil as Meera's mother\n* Harisree Martin as ''Sudevan''\n* Molly Kannamaly as ''Chala Miami''\n* KPAC Saji as Surendran Pillai\n* Thirumala Ramachandran as ''Kunaran''\n* Sumi Surendran as Advocate\n* Archana Menon \n* Gomathi Mahadevan\n* Girija Preman\n* Maneesh Krishna\n* Girija Raveendran\n* Anu\n* Shanavas Sharaf\n* Gracia Nikhila\n* Saniya Babu\n* Bindu Murali as ''Sasimohan's mother''\n;Guest Appearance \n* Biju Sopanam  (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* [[Nisha Sarang]] (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* [[Rishi S Kumar]] (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* Shivani (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* [[Al Sabith]] (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* [[Lakshmi Priya]] (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* Nelson (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* Aiswarya Rajeev (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* Sadhika Venugopal  (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* Stephy Grace (Episode 577)\n* Sarath Swamy(Episode 577)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLMzoNdm5sTvXc-VyR86IXzBawr028Ww-v YouTube link]\n\n[[Category:Indian television series]]\n[[Category:Indian television soap operas]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:2017 Indian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Indian drama television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian television series}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Seetha\n\u0d38\u0d40\u0d24\n| show_name_2              = \u0d38\u0d40\u0d24\n| image                    = Seetha_Serial_(Flowers_TV,_2017-present).jpg\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Drama]]<br />[[Romance film|Romance]]\n| producer                 = Binu.K.Ponnoose\n| writer                   = Dhanus\n| director                 = Girish Konni\n| company                  = BEE GEE Communications\n| starring                 = \n| opentheme                = Nizhalinte Nerukil Aardramai\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 674 \n| network                  = [[Flowers (TV channel)]]\n| country                  = [[India]]\n| location                 = \n| language                 = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]\n| editor                   = \n| cinematography           = \n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 20 Min approx.\n| picture_format           = [[1080i]] ([[HDTV]])\n| audio_format             = Keen FX\n| first_aired              = {{start date|df=yes|2017|2|20}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flowerstv.in/video/seetha-flowers-ep-01.cms|title=Seetha episode 1}}</ref>\n| last_aired               = \n{{end date|df=yes|2019|8|16}} \n| preceded_by              = Moonumani\n| followed_by              = \n| related                  = [[Chinthavishtayaya Seetha]]\n| website                  = https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLMzoNdm5sTvXc-VyR86IXzBawr028Ww-v\n| website_title            = Youtube link\n}}\n\n'''''Seetha''''' (Malayalam: \u0d38\u0d40\u0d24) is an [[Indian cinema|Indian]] [[television series]] in Malayalam language.\n\nThe series premiered from 20 February 2017 launched on [[Flowers (TV channel)|Flowers TV]] from Monday to Friday 7:00 PM.    \n, later changed to 6:30 PM  titled as  ''Seetha'' as a second part and with the same cast of the serial [[Chinthavishtayaya Seetha]]  aired on [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]]. In the first time of Malayalam television industry, a live shoot of an episode was telecasted on 5 August 2018 which showed ''Seetha-Indran'' marriage from 6:00 pm to 8:00 pm. It is one of the top rated serial on Malayalam Television and the lead pair [[Swasika ]] and [[Shanavas]] earned a huge fan base due to their on screen chemistry. The series also has a huge following on social media and Youtube Channel.\n\nThe show went off air on 16 August 2019.\nDue to the popularity of the show, the team is also planning to have a third season.\n{{div col|colwidth=}}\n\n== Plot ==\n\nSeetha is the only earning member of her family. She runs a family of her aged parents, her sister and her brother. Indran ([[Shanavas Shanu]]) being her moracherukkan (her father's sister's son) dreams of marrying her and is obsessed about his love for her. Sreeraman ([[Bipin Jose]]) and Seetha being college mates fall in love and decide to marry with the permission of their parents. Indran befriends [[Loan Shark]] Prathapan and later discovers that he also have enmity with Seetha as she refused to illegally allow him to do his business due to village panchayat rules. After lots of difficulties and hurdles, they finally marry. Much to their dismay, with the constant interference from Indran ([[Shanavas Shanu]]) and Shankaran Maman (Sreeraman's uncle), misunderstandings and fights crop in between them. Indran along with Prathapan plots to constantly destroy Seethas married life. In Parallel track, Indran who realises he can't get Seetha decides to marry Janaki ([[Ambili Devi]]) as a bid to show Seetha that he can have a happier married life. Unknowingly, he develops feelings for Janaki, to which she also reciprocates. Meanwhile a [[Loan Shark]] Prathapan now finds his plan of revenge to Seetha failing, plans to plot against Seetha and Indran by cunningly setting them up in a hotel room unknown to them and calls the press and gets them arrested. This incident sends shock waves to both Raman and Janaki. Raman and Seetha's relationship starts to further deteriorate. Seetha attempts suicide to which Indran comes as a savoir and takes her to hospital. Raman who rushes nick in time professes that he loves Seetha deeply, thus saving her from giving in to death. Seeing this, Indran develops a respectful attitude towards Seetha and gives up his revenge plan. Janaki, who fails to believe Indran, breaks her engagement. In a fit of rejection, Indran resorts alcoholism. Seetha, who feels equally responsible for ruining Indran's life, stops him from drinking by offering a position of being her angel guardian. As Sreeraman discovers that he is diagnosed with a brain tumor that's incurable, he decides to divorce Seetha out of love. He hides this ill fate from Seetha and divorces her. He then takes his childhood friend Janaki to accompany him for his treatment through natural medicine in an asram.\n\nMeanwhile, Indran, a changed man now, enters Seetha's life by asking her to marry him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/seetha-to-marry-indran/articleshow/64177184.cms|title=Seetha to marry Indran}}</ref> She, after being persuaded by her family and Vinayan sir decides to give love and marriage a second chance. Enter, Raman, who still claim to love Seetha but is shattered to know that Seetha has indeed moved on and will never be his.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/seetha-lashes-out-at-raman/articleshow/64510555.cms|title=Seetha leaves Raman}}</ref> Raman attempts suicide and is saved by his home nurse in the nick of time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/raman-contemplating-suicide/articleshow/64635283.cms|title=Raman attempts to take his life}}</ref> Seetha makes it clear to Raman that she would never marry him, making him think of his life in future. Seetha and Indran get married in a big grandeur.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/seetha-indran-wedding-to-go-live/articleshow/65258762.cms|title=Seetha-Indran marriage live on air}}</ref>. Enter Adi Lakshmi who claims to be the illegitimate daughter of Sreedharan. Indran and Seetha's marriage faces turbulances due to Indran keeping Adi Lakshmi's truth away. Meanwhile, Sreedharan decides to donate his kidney to the ailing Adi Lakshmi's mother as he is guilty of not been responsible all this while. \nSreeraman finds love for the second time and marries Devika with the presence of all his relatives and loved ones. During the wedding, Sreeraman's uncle, Prathapan and S.I. Sugunan conspires to kill Devika as a revenge, but Devika's father gets killed in process as he consumes the unknown poisonous juice that was meant for Devika. Devika and Devika's mother decide to live in Sreeram's home after their marriage.\n\n==Cast==\n\n;Lead cast\n* [[Swasika|Swasika Vijay]] as ''Seetha Indran''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/the-prime-time-beauties-of-malayalam-tv/articleshow/63972745.cms|title= Swasika as Seetha}}</ref>\n* [[Shanavas shanu]] as ''Indran''\n\n;Supporting cast\n* Sruthy Surendran (Manve) as ''Archana Giridhar''\n* [[Ambika Mohan]]/Roslin as ''Nalini''\n* T.S.Raju as ''Sreedharan''\n* Naveen Arakkal as ''Raghuvaran''\n* [[Ronson Vincent]] as ''Jatayu Dharman''\n* Shalu Kurian as ''Aadhilekshmi''\n* Bipin Jose as ''Sreeraman''<ref>\n{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/the-dapper-dudes/articleshow/64002122.cms|title= Bipin Jose as Sreeraman}}</ref>\n* Baby Riya as ''Charumol''\n*Gauri Krishna as ''Devika''\n* [[Ambili Devi]]  as ''Janaki''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/dance-is-what-i-am-the-most-passionate-about-ambili-devi/articleshow/61711677.cms|title= Ambili Devi as Janaki}}</ref>\n* Jaseela Parveen as ''Shreya Chacko Thattinpurath''\n* Varsha as ''Annamma''\n* Apsara as ''ACP Mariya / Mariyakutty''\n* Subhash Menon as \"Prathapan\"\n* Sabarinath as ''Sasimohan''\n* Sindhu Jacob as ''Aadhilekshmi's mother'' \n* Omana Ouseph as ''Saradamma''\n* Kishore as \"S.I Sugunan\"\n* Anzil Rahman as \"Mohan\"\n* Adhithyan Jayan as \"Anirudhan\"\n* Jijo Varghese Antony as \"C.I Madhavan\"\n;Earlier Cast\n* Harishanth as ''Vaishakhan/Minister''\n* Saranya Sasi as ''Vaidehi''\n* Kottayam Rashid as ''Karunan''\n*Amith as ''Mathukutty ''\n* Deepan Murali<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/seetha-actor-deepan-murali-gets-engaged/articleshow/62230031.cms|title= Deepan Murali aka Giri gets married}}</ref> as ''Giridhar''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/the-dapper-dudes/articleshow/64002122.cms|title= Deepan Murali as Giridhar}}</ref>\n* Manju Satheesh as ''Jaya Sree''\n* Faisal Razi as ''Ganesh''\n* [[Sajitha Betti]] as ''Adv.Fathima Beevi''\n* Baby Vaiga as ''Ganga Giridhar''\n* Ann maria as ''Meera''\n* [[Balachandran Chullikkadu]] as ''Guruji''\n* Prakrithi as ''Sreedevi''\n* Pratheeksha G. Pradeep as ''Mythili''\n* Saritha.B.Nair as ''Mrs.Vinayan''\n* [[Leona Lishoy|Lishoy]] as Meera's father\n* Sreedevi Anil as Meera's mother\n* Harisree Martin as ''Sudevan''\n* Molly Kannamaly as ''Chala Miami''\n* KPAC Saji as Surendran Pillai\n* Thirumala Ramachandran as ''Kunaran''\n* Sumi Surendran as Advocate\n* Archana Menon \n* Gomathi Mahadevan\n* Girija Preman\n* Maneesh Krishna\n* Girija Raveendran\n* Anu\n* Shanavas Sharaf\n* Gracia Nikhila\n* Saniya Babu\n* Bindu Murali as ''Sasimohan's mother''\n;Guest Appearance \n* Biju Sopanam  (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* [[Nisha Sarang]] (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* [[Rishi S Kumar]] (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* Shivani (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* [[Al Sabith]] (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* [[Lakshmi Priya]] (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* Nelson (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* Aiswarya Rajeev (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* Sadhika Venugopal  (Episode 411 \u2013 Seethakalyanam episode)\n* Stephy Grace (Episode 577)\n* Sarath Swamy(Episode 577)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLMzoNdm5sTvXc-VyR86IXzBawr028Ww-v YouTube link]\n\n[[Category:Indian television series]]\n[[Category:Indian television soap operas]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:2017 Indian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Malayalam-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Indian drama television series]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seetha_(serial)"}
{"title_page": "Escolta Street", "text_new": "{{Infobox street\n|image=Ph-mm-manila-binondo-escolta - east end (2014).JPG\n|caption=Escolta Street, looking west from Plaza Santa Cruz.\n|name=Escolta Street\n|alternate_name=Calle de la Escolta\n|length_km= 1.6\n|length_round=\n|length_ref=\n|direction_a=East\n|terminus_a=Plaza Santa Cruz, [[Santa Cruz, Manila|Santa Cruz]], [[Manila]]\n|junction=\n|direction_b=West\n|terminus_b=Plaza Moraga and Quintin Paredes Street, [[Binondo, Manila|Binondo]], [[Manila]]\n|previous_type=\n|previous_route=\n|next_type=\n|next_route=\n}}\n\n'''Escolta Street''' is a historic east-west street located in the old downtown district of [[Binondo, Manila|Binondo]] in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]. It runs parallel to the [[Pasig River]], from Plaza [[Santa Cruz, Manila|Santa Cruz]] to [[Plaza Moraga]] and Quintin Paredes Street. The street is home to several fine examples of early skyscraper design in the Philippines. In Spanish, it is known as ''calle de la Escolta''. Its definition as a historic financial district includes Escolta and other surrounding streets of [[Binondo, Manila|Binondo]] and [[Santa Cruz, Manila|Santa Cruz]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:EscoltaManila1899.jpg|left|thumb|An 1899 view of Escolta.]]\n[[File:Escolta St. circa 1941.jpg|thumb|Escolta Street in 1941.]]\nOne of the oldest streets in Manila, Escolta was created in 1594. Its name was derived from the Spanish word ''escoltar'', meaning \"to escort\".<ref>[http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/index.php/en/lifestyle/life/15211-a-walking-tour-of-escolta A Walking Tour of Escolta] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005001530/http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/index.php/en/lifestyle/life/15211-a-walking-tour-of-escolta |date=2013-10-05 }} published by Businessweek; accessed 8 September 2013</ref> Escolta was known for its concentration of immigrant merchants, mainly from [[Fujian]], [[China]], who came to make their fortune during the [[Manila-Acapulco Galleon]] trade. The street was lined with shops and boutiques selling imported goods from China, [[Europe]] and elsewhere in [[Latin America]] that arrived in the nearby port of [[San Nicolas, Manila|San Nicolas]]. By the late 19th century, Escolta flourished into a fashionable business district hosting the city's tallest buildings as well as the [[Manila Stock Exchange]]. The shops were replaced by modern department stores and an electric tram line known as ''tranvia'' plied the street. Escolta served as the city's primary commercial district until its decline in the 1960s when the center of business gradually shifted to [[Makati]].<ref>[http://bworldonline.com/content.php?section=SpecialFeature&title=Binondo-Back-Story&id=45475 Binondo Back Story] published by BusinessWorld; accessed 8 September 2013</ref>\n\n== In music ==\nThe first known reference to \"La Escolta\", can be heard on the zarzuela \"El pay-pay de Manila\"\n''Al volver de la Escolta Charito\ntras comprarse un precioso paipay,\ny una carta encontr\u00f3 de Pepito\nen su rocabay,\n\u00a1Ay, que se le cai!\nY en la carta le hablaba de amor\n\u00a1Ay Jes\u00fas, qu\u00e9 calor, qu\u00e9 calor!\n''\n\n==Architectural establishments==\n\n[[File:Ph-mm-manila-binondo-escolta - street view (2014).jpeg|thumb|Westward view of Escolta Street in 2014.]]\n\n* [[Don Roman Santos Building]]\n:A [[Neo-classical architecture|neo-classical]] building fronting Plaza Goiti (Lacson) in the eastern end of Escolta Street. The building once housed the headquarters of Monte de Piedad and Prudential Bank before it was sold to [[Bank of the Philippine Islands]].\n\n* [[First United Building]]\n:One of the few surviving examples of [[art deco]] architecture in Manila, it was the tallest building in Manila at the time of its completion in 1928. Designed by Andres Luna de San Pedro, the building was previously named Perez Samanillo Building.\n\n*[[El Hogar Filipino Building]]\n: A [[Neo-classical architecture|neo-classical]] and Renaissance building built as a wedding gift for the union of a Zobel daughter and a Peruvian count back in 1914. It was designed by Ramon Irureta-Goyena and Francisco Perez-Mu\u00f1oz in the Beaux Arts Style.\n\n* [[Regina Building]]\n:Built in 1934, this four-storey building was designed in the neo-classical style by Andres Luna de San Pedro.\n\n* [[Natividad Building]]\n:A [[Beaux-Arts architecture|beaux arts]] style building that housed the Insurance Commission in the 1950s.\n\n* [[Burke Building (Manila)|Burke Building]]\n:Named after philanthropist, [[William J. Burke]], the building is known as the location of the first elevator in Manila.\n\n* [[Calvo Building]]\n:Another fine example of [[Beaux-Arts architecture|beaux arts]] style architecture, it was built in 1938 by Edificio Calvo and designed by Fernando Ocampo. In 1950, the building was also the location of the first radio studio of [[DZBB-AM]] (a flagship AM radio station of [[GMA Network]]) until 1957 before the transferring of the DZBB studio in [[GMA Network Center]] (the current headquarters of GMA 7) along [[EDSA (road)|EDSA]] corner Timog Avenue, Diliman, [[Quezon City]].\n\n* [[Capitol Theater (Manila)|Capitol Theater]]\n:Designed by [[Juan Nakpil]] and built in the 1930s, this theater had a double balcony, which is a rare architectural design. The theater's facade has reliefs of 2 [[muses]] done by Francesco Monti. The theater is now closed, its location serving as a venue for a few commercial establishments and restaurants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinematreasures.org/theater/12378/ |title=Capitol Theater |publisher=Cinema Treasures |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Roman R. Santos Building.JPG|Roman R. Santos Building\nFile:Manilajf9487 39.JPG|First United Building (former Perez-Samanillo Building)\nFile:WTMP Flashbang B22-G.JPG|Regina Building north fa\u00e7ade viewed from the street\nFile:Street Vendors along Escolta.JPG|Street vendors in front of Regina Building at Escolta, Manila\nFile:Manilajf9532 11.JPG|[[Natividad Building]]\nFile:Burke Building, Escolta.JPG|[[Burke Building (Manila)|Burke Building]]\nFile:Calvo Building details 2.JPG|[[Calvo Building]] beaux-arts details\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Colon Street]]\n* [[Calle Real, Iloilo|Calle Real]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Escolta Street}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|14.3553|N|120.5843|E|source:frwiki_region:PH|format=dms|display=title}}\n{{Road infrastructure in Manila}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Manila]]\n[[Category:Binondo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox street\n|image=Ph-mm-manila-binondo-escolta - east end (2014).JPG\n|caption=Escolta Street, looking west from Plaza Santa Cruz.\n|name=Escolta Street\n|alternate_name=Calle de la Escolta\n|length_km= 1.6\n|length_round=\n|length_ref=\n|direction_a=East\n|terminus_a=Plaza Santa Cruz, [[Santa Cruz, Manila|Santa Cruz]], [[Manila]]\n|junction=\n|direction_b=West\n|terminus_b=Plaza Moraga and Quintin Paredes Street, [[Binondo, Manila|Binondo]], [[Manila]]\n|previous_type=\n|previous_route=\n|next_type=\n|next_route=\n}}\n\n'''Escolta Street''' is a historic east-west street located in the old downtown district of [[Binondo, Manila|Binondo]] in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]. It runs parallel to the [[Pasig River]], from Plaza [[Santa Cruz, Manila|Santa Cruz]] to [[Plaza Moraga]] and Quintin Paredes Street. The street is home to several fine examples of early skyscraper design in the Philippines. In Spanish, it is known as ''calle de la Escolta''. Its definition as a historic financial district includes Escolta and other surrounding streets of [[Binondo, Manila|Binondo]] and [[Santa Cruz, Manila|Santa Cruz]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:EscoltaManila1899.jpg|left|thumb|An 1899 view of Escolta.]]\n[[File:JMA14 Photo of Manila street.jpg|thumb|Escolta Street in 1941.]]\nOne of the oldest streets in Manila, Escolta was created in 1594. Its name was derived from the Spanish word ''escoltar'', meaning \"to escort\".<ref>[http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/index.php/en/lifestyle/life/15211-a-walking-tour-of-escolta A Walking Tour of Escolta] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005001530/http://www.businessmirror.com.ph/index.php/en/lifestyle/life/15211-a-walking-tour-of-escolta |date=2013-10-05 }} published by Businessweek; accessed 8 September 2013</ref> Escolta was known for its concentration of immigrant merchants, mainly from [[Fujian]], [[China]], who came to make their fortune during the [[Manila-Acapulco Galleon]] trade. The street was lined with shops and boutiques selling imported goods from China, [[Europe]] and elsewhere in [[Latin America]] that arrived in the nearby port of [[San Nicolas, Manila|San Nicolas]]. By the late 19th century, Escolta flourished into a fashionable business district hosting the city's tallest buildings as well as the [[Manila Stock Exchange]]. The shops were replaced by modern department stores and an electric tram line known as ''tranvia'' plied the street. Escolta served as the city's primary commercial district until its decline in the 1960s when the center of business gradually shifted to [[Makati]].<ref>[http://bworldonline.com/content.php?section=SpecialFeature&title=Binondo-Back-Story&id=45475 Binondo Back Story] published by BusinessWorld; accessed 8 September 2013</ref>\n\n== In music ==\nThe first known reference to \"La Escolta\", can be heard on the zarzuela \"El pay-pay de Manila\"\n''Al volver de la Escolta Charito\ntras comprarse un precioso paipay,\ny una carta encontr\u00f3 de Pepito\nen su rocabay,\n\u00a1Ay, que se le cai!\nY en la carta le hablaba de amor\n\u00a1Ay Jes\u00fas, qu\u00e9 calor, qu\u00e9 calor!\n''\n\n==Architectural establishments==\n\n[[File:Ph-mm-manila-binondo-escolta - street view (2014).jpeg|thumb|Westward view of Escolta Street in 2014.]]\n\n* [[Don Roman Santos Building]]\n:A [[Neo-classical architecture|neo-classical]] building fronting Plaza Goiti (Lacson) in the eastern end of Escolta Street. The building once housed the headquarters of Monte de Piedad and Prudential Bank before it was sold to [[Bank of the Philippine Islands]].\n\n* [[First United Building]]\n:One of the few surviving examples of [[art deco]] architecture in Manila, it was the tallest building in Manila at the time of its completion in 1928. Designed by Andres Luna de San Pedro, the building was previously named Perez Samanillo Building.\n\n*[[El Hogar Filipino Building]]\n: A [[Neo-classical architecture|neo-classical]] and Renaissance building built as a wedding gift for the union of a Zobel daughter and a Peruvian count back in 1914. It was designed by Ramon Irureta-Goyena and Francisco Perez-Mu\u00f1oz in the Beaux Arts Style.\n\n* [[Regina Building]]\n:Built in 1934, this four-storey building was designed in the neo-classical style by Andres Luna de San Pedro.\n\n* [[Natividad Building]]\n:A [[Beaux-Arts architecture|beaux arts]] style building that housed the Insurance Commission in the 1950s.\n\n* [[Burke Building (Manila)|Burke Building]]\n:Named after philanthropist, [[William J. Burke]], the building is known as the location of the first elevator in Manila.\n\n* [[Calvo Building]]\n:Another fine example of [[Beaux-Arts architecture|beaux arts]] style architecture, it was built in 1938 by Edificio Calvo and designed by Fernando Ocampo. In 1950, the building was also the location of the first radio studio of [[DZBB-AM]] (a flagship AM radio station of [[GMA Network]]) until 1957 before the transferring of the DZBB studio in [[GMA Network Center]] (the current headquarters of GMA 7) along [[EDSA (road)|EDSA]] corner Timog Avenue, Diliman, [[Quezon City]].\n\n* [[Capitol Theater (Manila)|Capitol Theater]]\n:Designed by [[Juan Nakpil]] and built in the 1930s, this theater had a double balcony, which is a rare architectural design. The theater's facade has reliefs of 2 [[muses]] done by Francesco Monti. The theater is now closed, its location serving as a venue for a few commercial establishments and restaurants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinematreasures.org/theater/12378/ |title=Capitol Theater |publisher=Cinema Treasures |date= |accessdate=2013-09-14}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Roman R. Santos Building.JPG|Roman R. Santos Building\nFile:Manilajf9487 39.JPG|First United Building (former Perez-Samanillo Building)\nFile:WTMP Flashbang B22-G.JPG|Regina Building north fa\u00e7ade viewed from the street\nFile:Street Vendors along Escolta.JPG|Street vendors in front of Regina Building at Escolta, Manila\nFile:Manilajf9532 11.JPG|[[Natividad Building]]\nFile:Burke Building, Escolta.JPG|[[Burke Building (Manila)|Burke Building]]\nFile:Calvo Building details 2.JPG|[[Calvo Building]] beaux-arts details\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Colon Street]]\n* [[Calle Real, Iloilo|Calle Real]]\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Escolta Street}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|14.3553|N|120.5843|E|source:frwiki_region:PH|format=dms|display=title}}\n{{Road infrastructure in Manila}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Manila]]\n[[Category:Binondo]]\n", "name_user": "Fridolin freudenfett", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:JMA14 Photo of Manila street.jpg\u2192File:Escolta St. circa 1941.jpgCriterion 2(meaningless or ambiguous name)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Escolta_Street"}
{"title_page": "1974 Stockholm Open \u2013 Doubles", "text_new": "{{Tennis events|1974|Stockholm Open|s\n| defchamp = \n| champ    = {{flagicon|NED}} [[Tom Okker]]<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marty Riessen]]\n| runner   = {{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Bob Hewitt]]<br />{{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Frew McMillan]]\n| score    = 2\u20136, 6\u20133, 6\u20134\n| edition  = \n| type     = singles doubles\n}}\n{{main|1974 Stockholm Open}}\n\n[[Jimmy Connors]] and [[Ilie N\u0103stase]] were the defending champions, but Riessen did not participate this year.  Okker partnered [[Arthur Ashe]], losing in the quarterfinals.\n\n[[Tom Okker]] and [[Marty Riessen]] won the title, defeating [[Bob Hewitt]] and [[Frew McMillan]] 2\u20136, 6\u20133, 6\u20134 in the final.\n\n==Seeds==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n# {{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Bob Hewitt]] / {{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Frew McMillan]] ''(Final)''\n# '''{{flagicon|NED}} [[Tom Okker]] / {{flagicon|USA}} [[Marty Riessen]] (Champions)'''\n}}\n\n==Draw==\n{{Draw key}}\n\n===Finals===\n{{4TeamBracket-Tennis3\n| RD1=Semifinals\n| RD2=Final\n| team-width=175\n\n| RD1-seed1=1\n| RD1-team1='''{{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Bob Hewitt]]<br>{{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Frew McMillan]]'''\n| RD1-score1-1='''6'''\n| RD1-score1-2=3\n| RD1-score1-3='''6'''\n| RD1-seed2=&nbsp;\n| RD1-team2={{flagicon|SWE}} [[Rolf Norberg]]<br>{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Tenny Svensson]]\n| RD1-score2-1=3\n| RD1-score2-2='''6'''\n| RD1-score2-3=3\n\n| RD1-seed3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-team3={{flagicon|USA}} [[Charlie Pasarell]]<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[Erik van Dillen]]\n| RD1-score3-1=5\n| RD1-score3-2=5\n| RD1-score3-3=&nbsp;\n| RD1-seed4=2\n| RD1-team4='''{{flagicon|NED}} [[Tom Okker]]<br>{{flagicon|USA}} [[Marty Riessen]]'''\n| RD1-score4-1='''7'''\n| RD1-score4-2='''7'''\n| RD1-score4-3=&nbsp;\n\n| RD2-seed1=1\n| RD2-team1={{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Bob Hewitt]]<br>{{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Frew McMillan]]\n| RD2-score1-1='''6'''\n| RD2-score1-2=3\n| RD2-score1-3=4\n| RD2-seed2=2\n| RD2-team2='''{{flagicon