.0%\n|-\n| 2018 || 7,127,168 || {{increase}} 7.7%\n|-\n| 2019 || 8,260,913 || {{increase}} 15.24%\n|}\n\n==Attractions==\n[[File:Foggy_Ifugao_Rice_Terraces.jpg|thumb|[[Rice Terraces of the Philippine Cordilleras]], [[World Heritage Site]].]]\n\n{{Main|Philippine Registry of Cultural Property|Wildlife of the Philippines|List of protected areas of the Philippines}}\n\n===Immovable Tangible Heritage===\n{{Main|List of World Heritage Sites in the Philippines|List of Ramsar sites in the Philippines|ASEAN Heritage Parks|Dambana|List of protected areas of the Philippines}}\nThe Philippines has at least 144 distinct ethno-linguistic groups (all are classified as Filipinos, both mainstream and indigenous, by the government), each having their own distinct cultures. Each region of the Philippines has different traditions, honed and conserved by numerous ethnic groups distinct from each other. Currently, there are '''six [[UNESCO]] World Heritage Sites''' scattered in nine different locations (Vigan, [[Santa Maria Church]] Complex, [[Paoay Church]] Complex, San Agustin Church Complex, [[Miagao Church]] Complex, Rice Terraces of the Cordilleras which includes five different rice terrace clusters, Tubbataha Reefs Natural Park, Underground River of Puerto Princesa, and [[Mount Hamiguitan]] Wildlife Sanctaury), '''two UNESCO World Heritage Cities''' ([[Vigan]] and [[Miagao]]), '''one UNESCO Creative City''' ([[Baguio]]), '''three UNESCO Biosphere Reserves''' ([[Palawan]] Biosphere Reserve, [[Albay]] Biosphere Reserve, and [[Puerto Galera]] Biosphere Reserve), '''seven [[List of Ramsar sites in the Philippines|Ramsar Wetland Sites]]''' ([[Las Pi\u00f1as-Para\u00f1aque Critical Habitat and Ecotourism Area|Las Pi\u00f1as-Para\u00f1aque]], [[Naujan Lake National Park|Lake Naujan]], [[Puerto Princesa Subterranean River National Park|Puerto Princesa]], [[Tubbataha Reefs Natural Park|Tubbataha Reefs]], [[Olango Island Wildlife Sanctuary|Olango]], [[Agusan Marsh Wildlife Sanctuary|Agusan Marsh]], and [[Negros Occidental]] Coastal Wetlands), and '''eight [[ASEAN]] Heritage Parks''' (Mount Apo National Park, Mounts Iglit-Baco  National Park, Mount kitanglad  National Park, Mount Makiling  National Park, Tubbataha Reefs Natural Park, Mount Hamiguitan Wildlife Sanctuary, and Timpoong-Hibok-Hibok  National Park) in the Philippines. The last three lists reinforces the title of the Philippines as one of the [[biodiversity hotspot]]s declared by [[Conservation International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.conservation.org/How/Pages/Hotspots.aspx |title=Why Hotspots Matter - Conservation International |publisher=Conservation.org |date=2015-11-20 |accessdate=2018-03-29}}</ref> The following are the most significant natural and cultural heritage sites of the Philippines, including sea territories:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n!  style=\"text-align:center; background:#abcdef;\"| Region\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n!  style=\"text-align:center; background:#abcdef;\"| Attractions\n|- \n! [[Ilocos Region]]\n| [[Baroque Churches of the Philippines|Churches of Ilocandia]] (includes [[Paoay Church]], UNESCO World Heritage Site and [[Santa Maria Church]], UNESCO World Heritage Site) \u2022 [[Vigan]], UNESCO World Heritage Site \u2022 [[Bolinao, Pangasinan|Bolinao]] \u2022 Heritage Railways and Stations of Luzon \u2022 [[Spanish Colonial Fortifications of the Philippines]] \u2022 [[Laoag]]\n|-\n! [[Cordillera Administrative Region]]\n| [[Rice Terraces of the Philippine Cordilleras]], UNESCO World Heritage Site \u2022 [[Baroque Churches of the Philippines|Churches of Cordillera]] \u2022 [[Kabayan Mummies|Kabayan Mummy Burial Caves]] \u2022  Alab Petroglyphs \u2022 [[Mount Pulag]] \u2022 [[Baguio City]], UNESCO Creative City \u2022 [[Lubuagan]] \u2022 [[Kiangan]] \u2022 [[Sagada]] \u2022 [[Balbalasang-Balbalan National Park]] \u2022 [[Cassamata Hill National Park]] \u2022 [[Mount Data National Park]]\n|-\n! [[Cagayan Valley]]\n| [[Baroque Churches of the Philippines|Churches of Cagayan Valley]] (including [[Tumauini Church]]) \u2022 [[Batanes]] \u2022 [[Lal-lo and Gattaran Shell Middens]] \u2022 [[Sierra Madre (Philippines)|Sierra Madre Range]] \u2022 Penablanca Petrographs \u2022 Paleolithic Archaeological Sites in Cagayan Valley (including Awidon Mesa Formation and Callao Limestone Formation) \u2022 [[Benham Rise|Kalipung-awan (Philippine) Rise]]\n|-\n! [[Central Luzon]]\n| [[Malolos]] \u2022 [[Baler]] \u2022 [[Baroque Churches of the Philippines|Churches of Central Luzon]] \u2022 [[Mount Pinatubo]] \u2022 [[Sierra Madre (Philippines)|Sierra Madre Range]] \u2022 [[Zambales Mountains]] \u2022 Heritage Railways and Stations of Luzon \u2022 [[San Fernando, Pampanga|San Fernando]] \u2022 [[Spanish Colonial Fortifications of the Philippines]] \u2022 Bataan Monuments on World War II \u2022 [[Pampanga]] Sugar Central Sites \u2022 Historic Rice Plantations of Tarlac (including [[Hacienda Luisita]]) \u2022 [[Benham Rise|Kalipung-awan (Philippine) Rise]] \u2022 [[Candaba Swamp]] \u2022 [[Subic Bay|Subic]] \u2022 [[Angeles City]] \u2022 [[Minalungao National Park]]\n|-\n! [[Metro Manila]]\n| [[Baroque Churches of the Philippines|Churches of Manila]] (including [[San Agustin Church (Manila)|San Agustin Church]], UNESCO World Heritage Site, [[Tondo Church]], [[Binondo Church]], [[Quiapo Church]], [[San Sebastian Church (Manila)|San Sebastian Church]], [[Malate Church]], [[Santa Ana Church]], and [[Ermita Church]]) \u2022 [[Intramuros]] \u2022 [[Rizal Park]] (including the [[National Museum of the Philippines]], [[Rizal Monument]], and the [[National Library of the Philippines]]) \u2022 [[University of Santo Tomas]] \u2022 Heritage Railways and Stations of Luzon \u2022 [[Spanish Colonial Fortifications of the Philippines]] \u2022 National Monuments of Manila (including the [[People Power Monument]]) \u2022 [[Las Pi\u00f1as-Para\u